vectorData.altText: 3. The venous blood-filled spaces on either side of the sella turcica are the ______________ sinuses.
That’s right! The cavernous sinuses on either side of the sella turcica collect venous blood from the face and the base of the brain.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
Identify the body of the sphenoid bone, a feature of which is the sella turcica or pituitary fossa.

Put an index finger and thumb on either side of the sella turcica; this is the location of the cavernous sinuses, which receive venous blood from the face, via the ophthalmic veins, as well as from the base of the brain.

Note that the petrous temporal bone tucks in under the greater wing of the sphenoid bone and that a portion of the petrous bone faces upward to contribute to the floor of the middle cranial fossa. Identify the sharp dividing line between the middle and posterior fossae, the petrous ridge.
